1
00:00:12,603 --> 00:00:15,793
[SPEAKER_02]: We're live in Salford for a TV first.

2
00:00:15,813 --> 00:00:19,184
[SPEAKER_02]: It's Boris Johnson versus Jeremy Corbyn.

3
00:00:20,167 --> 00:00:21,752
[SPEAKER_02]: The ITV debate.

4
00:00:44,007 --> 00:00:44,508
[SPEAKER_02]: Good evening.

5
00:00:44,568 --> 00:00:51,075
[SPEAKER_02]: In just over three weeks, we'll be voting in what many think is the most important general election of our lifetimes.

6
00:00:51,155 --> 00:01:02,168
[SPEAKER_02]: Tonight, the Conservative Prime Minister Boris Johnson and the leader of the Labour Party, Jeremy Corbyn, debate face-to-face, responding to questions from ITV viewers.

7
00:01:02,588 --> 00:01:05,712
[SPEAKER_02]: And you at home can take part too using the hashtag

8
00:01:05,692 --> 00:01:07,094
[SPEAKER_02]: ITV debate.

9
00:01:07,354 --> 00:01:22,013
[SPEAKER_02]: Later tonight at 10 o'clock, you'll be able to see other leaders on ITV when Lib Dem Joe Swinson, the SNP's Nicola Sturgeon, the Brexit Party's Nigel Farage and Green Party co-leader Sian Berry will be interviewed live by Nina Hussain.

10
00:01:22,354 --> 00:01:26,559
[SPEAKER_02]: But now it's time for Boris Johnson versus Jeremy Corbyn.

11
00:01:26,579 --> 00:01:31,886
[SPEAKER_02]: Before we take our first question tonight, they'll each now make an opening statement.

12
00:01:32,026 --> 00:01:33,488
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr Corbyn, it's over to you.

13
00:01:34,312 --> 00:01:37,987
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Julie, and to everyone watching this debate tonight.

14
00:01:38,730 --> 00:01:42,988
[SPEAKER_17]: This election gives you a real choice about your future.

15
00:01:43,762 --> 00:01:47,085
[SPEAKER_17]: the future of your community and of our country.

16
00:01:47,786 --> 00:01:50,729
[SPEAKER_17]: Labour is offering real change and real hope.

17
00:01:51,550 --> 00:01:56,755
[SPEAKER_17]: We will build a fairer Britain that cares for all, where wealth and power are shared.

18
00:01:57,455 --> 00:01:59,257
[SPEAKER_17]: The Conservative government is failing.

19
00:01:59,718 --> 00:02:06,184
[SPEAKER_17]: It's failed on the economy, on the climate crisis, the National Health Service and on Brexit.

20
00:02:06,204 --> 00:02:13,431
[SPEAKER_17]: We will get Brexit sorted by giving you, the people, the final say and implement whatever you decide.

21
00:02:14,373 --> 00:02:22,323
[SPEAKER_17]: Too many families are without a proper home, struggling to make ends meet, while tax cuts are handed to the super-rich.

22
00:02:22,984 --> 00:02:27,349
[SPEAKER_17]: We can do better than this, with a Labour government on your side.

23
00:02:27,790 --> 00:02:34,238
[SPEAKER_17]: A Labour government for the many, not just the few.

24
00:02:42,622 --> 00:02:43,604
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Julian.

25
00:02:43,684 --> 00:02:44,545
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Mr Corbyn.

26
00:02:44,565 --> 00:02:47,711
[SPEAKER_04]: There's only one reason why we're having this election.

27
00:02:47,731 --> 00:02:52,539
[SPEAKER_04]: That is that we have a deadlocked parliament that will not deliver Brexit.

28
00:02:52,559 --> 00:03:01,755
[SPEAKER_04]: And whether you voted for leave or remain, people want to get Brexit done and to unleash the potential of this entire country.

29
00:03:02,156 --> 00:03:04,680
[SPEAKER_04]: And we Conservatives can.

30
00:03:04,660 --> 00:03:15,834
[SPEAKER_04]: Because if you vote for us, we have a deal that is ready to go, approved by every one of the 635 Conservative candidates standing at this election.

31
00:03:16,174 --> 00:03:23,343
[SPEAKER_04]: And as soon as we can get that deal through Parliament, as we can in the next few weeks, we can get on with the people's priorities.

32
00:03:23,603 --> 00:03:25,285
[SPEAKER_04]: And that's the choice.

33
00:03:25,265 --> 00:03:35,616
[SPEAKER_04]: dither and delay, deadlock and division under a Corbyn-Sturgeon coalition with two referendums, another one on the EU and then another one on Scotland.

34
00:03:35,976 --> 00:03:49,250
[SPEAKER_04]: Or we can end this national misery, break the deadlock, get Brexit done, and make 2020 a year of prosperity and growth where we invest in our NHS and deal with the cost of living.

35
00:03:49,530 --> 00:03:52,573
[SPEAKER_04]: Together, let's take this country forwards.

36
00:03:53,054 --> 00:03:54,175
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Mr Johnson.

37
00:03:59,352 --> 00:04:03,136
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, we invited viewers from right across the country to submit questions.

38
00:04:03,196 --> 00:04:06,820
[SPEAKER_02]: We've selected the questioners, and they are in the studio with us this evening.

39
00:04:06,840 --> 00:04:09,202
[SPEAKER_02]: The two leaders don't know what they'll be asked.

40
00:04:09,382 --> 00:04:12,706
[SPEAKER_02]: Also here, the people who will listen to tonight's debate.

41
00:04:12,786 --> 00:04:19,853
[SPEAKER_02]: Some have voted Conservative and some Labour in the past, and some have voted for other parties across the UK.

42
00:04:19,913 --> 00:04:24,077
[SPEAKER_02]: And our first question tonight comes from Cath Sherlock from Bradford.

43
00:04:25,289 --> 00:04:31,645
[SPEAKER_14]: Both of you have promised that Brexit will be resolved in the next few months, but you're really telling us the truth.

44
00:04:32,406 --> 00:04:34,331
[SPEAKER_14]: There have been so many broken promises.

45
00:04:34,993 --> 00:04:39,163
[SPEAKER_14]: Can you reassure me that we will not be talking about this forever?

46
00:04:40,342 --> 00:04:42,486
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed, Kath.

47
00:04:42,506 --> 00:04:45,311
[SPEAKER_02]: So a question about the timetable for Brexit.

48
00:04:45,792 --> 00:04:48,316
[SPEAKER_02]: To respond first, Mr Johnson.

49
00:04:49,017 --> 00:04:50,340
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, thank you very much, Kath.

50
00:04:50,360 --> 00:04:57,272
[SPEAKER_04]: And yes, we certainly will come out on January the 31st, because we have a deal that, as I say, is oven ready.

51
00:04:57,312 --> 00:04:58,975
[SPEAKER_04]: It's ready to go.

52
00:04:58,955 --> 00:05:06,689
[SPEAKER_04]: And it's approved, as I say, not just by our friends and partners in the EU, but by every one of the 635 Conservative candidates.

53
00:05:06,770 --> 00:05:10,577
[SPEAKER_04]: And it delivers everything that we wanted from Brexit.

54
00:05:10,717 --> 00:05:14,224
[SPEAKER_04]: Our whole country comes out entire and perfect.

55
00:05:14,244 --> 00:05:16,628
[SPEAKER_04]: England, Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland together.

56
00:05:17,069 --> 00:05:20,355
[SPEAKER_04]: And there is a sharp distinction between what we are proposing

57
00:05:20,335 --> 00:05:23,399
[SPEAKER_04]: getting Brexit done, unleashing the potential of this country.

58
00:05:23,800 --> 00:05:36,498
[SPEAKER_04]: And next year, dither and delay with another referendum on the EU when Jeremy Corbyn, Mr Corbyn, cannot tell us which side he would campaign on in that referendum.

59
00:05:36,518 --> 00:05:37,339
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, thank you, Mr Johnson.

60
00:05:37,359 --> 00:05:41,044
[SPEAKER_02]: Your time's up for your first response, your first response to Kath's question.

61
00:05:41,024 --> 00:05:43,648
[SPEAKER_17]: Our priority is obviously to get it sorted.

62
00:05:44,049 --> 00:06:02,279
[SPEAKER_17]: We will, within three months, negotiate a credible leave option with the European Union and within six months put that to a referendum of the British people to decide between that option of leaving whilst protecting jobs and trade and the Good Friday Agreement with Europe or remaining as full members of the European Union.

63
00:06:02,579 --> 00:06:04,703
[SPEAKER_17]: That will be the choice put before the British people.

64
00:06:05,084 --> 00:06:05,985
[SPEAKER_17]: The idea

65
00:06:05,965 --> 00:06:12,455
[SPEAKER_17]: that the Prime Minister Boris Johnson's deal can be dealt with and finished by the end of January is such nonsense.

66
00:06:12,716 --> 00:06:23,332
[SPEAKER_17]: What he's proposing is a trade deal with the United States that would take at least seven years to negotiate, whilst at the same time saying he would negotiate a special trade deal with the European Union.

67
00:06:23,613 --> 00:06:25,756
[SPEAKER_17]: The two things are actually incompatible.

68
00:06:25,976 --> 00:06:27,619
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr Corbyn.

69
00:06:34,231 --> 00:06:47,289
[SPEAKER_02]: So to open the debate, Mr Johnson said that he claims he has a deal that is ready to go, that you would have to negotiate a new deal after three years since we voted to lead the European Union.

70
00:06:47,429 --> 00:06:49,455
[SPEAKER_02]: On that point, how would you respond?

71
00:06:49,435 --> 00:07:04,270
[SPEAKER_17]: Well the Prime Minister Boris Johnson voted twice against Theresa May's deal, one time for it, then proposed his own deal which narrowly got through the House of Commons with the support of the DUP, which is actually even worse than Theresa May's deal.

72
00:07:04,451 --> 00:07:05,453
[SPEAKER_17]: He cannot

73
00:07:05,433 --> 00:07:08,379
[SPEAKER_17]: protect jobs in this country on that basis.

74
00:07:08,820 --> 00:07:16,177
[SPEAKER_17]: And I think it is time that we actually recognise we have to maintain a firm and good trading relationship with Europe.

75
00:07:16,197 --> 00:07:21,889
[SPEAKER_17]: Otherwise, more jobs will be lost all over the country as they've already been lost because of the uncertainty.

76
00:07:21,869 --> 00:07:33,103
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, we have a great deal that is supported, as Mr Corbyn says, not just by many members of his own party, but by the entire Conservative Party now.

77
00:07:33,163 --> 00:07:36,727
[SPEAKER_04]: And 635 Conservative candidates have backed it.

78
00:07:37,288 --> 00:07:39,450
[SPEAKER_04]: And what is the alternative?

79
00:07:39,951 --> 00:07:45,177
[SPEAKER_04]: It's under Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party to consecrate next year

80
00:07:45,157 --> 00:07:54,889
[SPEAKER_04]: to a three-month extension in which Mr Corbyn proposes to negotiate a new treaty, and then to put that to the people in a referendum.

81
00:07:55,089 --> 00:08:00,756
[SPEAKER_04]: But we don't know, and I've asked this before, we don't know on which side Mr Corbyn would campaign.

82
00:08:01,096 --> 00:08:03,499
[SPEAKER_04]: Is he going to campaign for leave or remain?

83
00:08:03,559 --> 00:08:05,541
[SPEAKER_02]: Can we ask Mr Corbyn to respond to that?

84
00:08:05,561 --> 00:08:06,963
[SPEAKER_17]: Very clearly, we will.

85
00:08:08,425 --> 00:08:08,785
[SPEAKER_17]: We will negotiate.

86
00:08:10,790 --> 00:08:17,362
[SPEAKER_17]: We will negotiate an agreement and we will put that alongside remain in a referendum.

87
00:08:17,802 --> 00:08:20,087
[SPEAKER_17]: And our government will abide by that result.

88
00:08:20,267 --> 00:08:22,531
[SPEAKER_17]: I will carry out the result of that referendum.

89
00:08:22,551 --> 00:08:28,782
[SPEAKER_17]: There will be a genuine choice put before the people of Britain to make their decision and we will carry it out.

90
00:08:34,077 --> 00:08:39,422
[SPEAKER_04]: At this election, what we're asking is for a mandate to govern.

91
00:08:39,442 --> 00:08:46,368
[SPEAKER_04]: And Mr Corbyn is asking the people for a mandate to conduct a new negotiation next year when we don't need one, because we've already got a deal.

92
00:08:46,629 --> 00:08:53,195
[SPEAKER_04]: I think what people need to understand is whether he believes in the deal that he is proposing to do.

93
00:08:53,795 --> 00:08:56,177
[SPEAKER_04]: Does he actually want to do this deal?

94
00:08:56,318 --> 00:09:02,143
[SPEAKER_04]: Because if he doesn't believe in it, or if, absurdly, he was then going to campaign against it,

95
00:09:02,123 --> 00:09:03,444
[SPEAKER_04]: in the forthcoming referendum.

96
00:09:03,504 --> 00:09:05,266
[SPEAKER_04]: Perhaps you'd like to put the question directly to Mr Corbyn.

97
00:09:05,286 --> 00:09:07,429
[SPEAKER_04]: What is the point of Brussels offering him?

98
00:09:07,449 --> 00:09:08,230
[SPEAKER_04]: Put the question to Mr Corbyn.

99
00:09:08,290 --> 00:09:13,195
[SPEAKER_04]: And I wonder whether Mr Corbyn can now tell us, are you going to campaign for leave or remain?

100
00:09:13,215 --> 00:09:22,505
[SPEAKER_17]: I want to bring people together, therefore there will be a referendum in which that decision will be made by the British people and our government will abide by that decision.

101
00:09:22,805 --> 00:09:25,228
[SPEAKER_17]: When you say you'll get it done,

102
00:09:25,478 --> 00:09:32,426
[SPEAKER_17]: Really, Mr. Johnson, you are going to embark on probably seven years of negotiations with the United States on a trade deal.

103
00:09:32,847 --> 00:09:40,516
[SPEAKER_17]: You've already indicated that you will allow our National Health Service to be put at risk by a trade deal with the United States.

104
00:09:41,036 --> 00:09:46,743
[SPEAKER_17]: You've already indicated that you would do a Canada-style agreement, which took at least seven years to negotiate.

105
00:09:47,063 --> 00:09:51,148
[SPEAKER_17]: So you're not going to get it done in a few months, and you know that perfectly well.

106
00:09:56,022 --> 00:10:08,457
[SPEAKER_02]: I'm noting here, of course, that we haven't heard whether you would campaign for Remain or leave in that situation, but it is important that we put the point that you have just made directly to Mr Johnson about this timetable.

107
00:10:08,757 --> 00:10:10,219
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's have a look at the timetable.

108
00:10:10,279 --> 00:10:16,166
[SPEAKER_02]: You reckon that you can get your divorce deal done and a trade deal done by December 2020.

109
00:10:16,467 --> 00:10:20,351
[SPEAKER_02]: Do you stick on a pledge on that deadline of December 2020?

110
00:10:20,792 --> 00:10:21,793
[SPEAKER_02]: Have you dug yourself a new

111
00:10:21,773 --> 00:10:22,934
[SPEAKER_04]: Yeah, absolutely.

112
00:10:22,974 --> 00:10:29,941
[SPEAKER_04]: Because people said, don't forget, people said that we couldn't do a new deal in three months.

113
00:10:30,361 --> 00:10:33,224
[SPEAKER_04]: People said that they would never open up the treaty.

114
00:10:33,244 --> 00:10:34,605
[SPEAKER_04]: They said it was impossible to do.

115
00:10:34,946 --> 00:10:36,207
[SPEAKER_04]: Actually, we succeeded.

116
00:10:36,227 --> 00:10:40,791
[SPEAKER_04]: And we have a great new deal that, as I say, is oven ready, ready to go.

117
00:10:41,031 --> 00:10:44,314
[SPEAKER_04]: And I hear what Jeremy Corbyn has to say about it.

118
00:10:44,354 --> 00:10:46,617
[SPEAKER_02]: Would you mint a new coin for December 2020?

119
00:10:47,037 --> 00:10:50,160
[SPEAKER_04]: I hear what people say about it.

120
00:10:50,748 --> 00:11:04,064
[SPEAKER_04]: No, we have ample time to do a fantastic free trade deal with our friends and partners in the EU, because we're already in a state of perfect alignment, both for tariffs and for quotas.

121
00:11:04,244 --> 00:11:05,846
[SPEAKER_04]: And we still have not heard, Julie.

122
00:11:05,906 --> 00:11:06,487
[SPEAKER_04]: You will notice.

123
00:11:06,928 --> 00:11:08,049
[SPEAKER_04]: I've answered your questions.

124
00:11:08,069 --> 00:11:10,792
[SPEAKER_04]: But there is a glaring lacuna still in this debate.

125
00:11:10,953 --> 00:11:12,975
[SPEAKER_04]: We still don't know.

126
00:11:12,955 --> 00:11:17,180
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm sorry to say, we still don't know.

127
00:11:17,220 --> 00:11:18,742
[SPEAKER_04]: There is a vast emanation.

128
00:11:19,203 --> 00:11:19,704
[SPEAKER_04]: OK.

129
00:11:19,884 --> 00:11:22,407
[SPEAKER_04]: Allow Mr. Corbyn to respond to the question from Mr. Johnson.

130
00:11:22,427 --> 00:11:25,992
[SPEAKER_04]: Is Jeremy Corbyn going to campaign for the deal he proposes to do?

131
00:11:26,392 --> 00:11:31,298
[SPEAKER_04]: Or is he going to invite his Labour colleagues to destroy the contraption that he's created?

132
00:11:31,318 --> 00:11:33,281
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, let's allow Mr. Corbyn to respond to that.

133
00:11:33,381 --> 00:11:33,922
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

134
00:11:33,942 --> 00:11:37,326
[SPEAKER_17]: That's what I've said, and it's very clear, very clear.

135
00:11:37,306 --> 00:11:43,133
[SPEAKER_17]: Three months to negotiate, six months for a referendum, and that will bring that process to an end.

136
00:11:43,413 --> 00:11:59,391
[SPEAKER_17]: What we know of the government's proposals, what we know of what Mr. Johnson has done is a series of secret meetings with the United States in which they were proposing to open up our NHS markets, as they call them, to American companies.

137
00:11:59,791 --> 00:12:04,697
[SPEAKER_17]: Freedom of Information Act request was made in order to find out what happened at these meetings.

138
00:12:04,677 --> 00:12:05,959
[SPEAKER_17]: That's what happened at these meetings.

139
00:12:06,520 --> 00:12:09,544
[SPEAKER_17]: Every single line of this document redacted out.

140
00:12:10,025 --> 00:12:15,093
[SPEAKER_17]: A document here, a document here of US-UK negotiations.

141
00:12:15,554 --> 00:12:18,178
[SPEAKER_17]: Summary of specific negotiating objectives.

142
00:12:18,198 --> 00:12:22,645
[SPEAKER_17]: Full market access for US products to our National Health Service.

143
00:12:22,845 --> 00:12:28,153
[SPEAKER_17]: You're going to sell our National Health Service out to the United States and Big Pharma.

144
00:12:28,133 --> 00:12:32,402
[SPEAKER_04]: This is an absolute invention.

145
00:12:32,843 --> 00:12:34,306
[SPEAKER_04]: It is completely untrue.

146
00:12:34,606 --> 00:12:44,287
[SPEAKER_04]: There are no circumstances, whatever, in which this government or any conservative government will put the NHS on the table in any trade negotiation.

147
00:12:44,447 --> 00:12:46,952
[SPEAKER_04]: Our NHS will never be for sale.

148
00:12:46,932 --> 00:12:48,675
[SPEAKER_04]: And I'm amazed how often this comes up.

149
00:12:48,695 --> 00:13:02,019
[SPEAKER_04]: The only reason that it comes up is because Mr. Corbyn is trying to conceal the void at the heart of his Brexit policy and refusing to answer the question of which side, which side he would take.

150
00:13:02,039 --> 00:13:05,325
[SPEAKER_04]: Because the public still, the public have a right, the public have a right to know.

151
00:13:05,345 --> 00:13:05,966
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay, thank you Mr. Corbyn.

152
00:13:06,006 --> 00:13:07,669
[SPEAKER_20]: Just very, just very briefly.

153
00:13:07,870 --> 00:13:09,052
[SPEAKER_17]: I've made the position clear.

154
00:13:09,332 --> 00:13:10,915
[SPEAKER_17]: We will have a referendum.

155
00:13:10,895 --> 00:13:15,120
[SPEAKER_17]: We will have negotiations, and we will abide by that result.

156
00:13:15,360 --> 00:13:18,004
[SPEAKER_17]: It's the British people who will make that decision.

157
00:13:18,104 --> 00:13:19,285
[SPEAKER_17]: Yes, we've heard that.

158
00:13:19,385 --> 00:13:20,166
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr. Corbyn.

159
00:13:20,186 --> 00:13:20,807
[SPEAKER_17]: We've heard that.

160
00:13:20,847 --> 00:13:35,485
[SPEAKER_17]: I do think, though, that since the Prime Minister has claimed the NHS is not under threat, why then did his government agree with the US that there should be, in the terms of negotiations, full market access for United States medical companies

161
00:13:35,465 --> 00:13:37,647
[SPEAKER_17]: into our national health service.

162
00:13:37,667 --> 00:13:40,870
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, we're going to talk about the NHS a little further a little later.

163
00:13:41,391 --> 00:13:44,974
[SPEAKER_02]: And we're now going to go to our next questioner.

164
00:13:45,014 --> 00:13:53,422
[SPEAKER_02]: Staying with the issue of Brexit, John Firth wants to ask about the possible threat to the Union, which could mean the breakup of the United Kingdom.

165
00:13:53,662 --> 00:13:53,802
[SPEAKER_02]: John.

166
00:13:54,223 --> 00:13:56,845
[SPEAKER_04]: Is the Union worth sacrificing for Brexit?

167
00:13:58,147 --> 00:13:59,888
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed for that.

168
00:14:00,048 --> 00:14:03,852
[SPEAKER_02]: Is the Union worth sacrificing for Brexit, Mr Corbyn?

169
00:14:04,726 --> 00:14:31,442
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, I hope the union is not going to be broken up or sacrificed in this way, but the agreements that the Prime Minister negotiated or he's put, not negotiated, he's put towards the Parliament was about creating a border between the Republic of Ireland and Northern Ireland, creating a different customs arrangement for Northern Ireland with the rest of Ireland, having promised to the Democratic Unionist Party he would never do that.

170
00:14:31,422 --> 00:14:33,224
[SPEAKER_17]: Clearly, there is an issue there.

171
00:14:33,524 --> 00:14:37,409
[SPEAKER_17]: Clearly, there are issues all around about this deal that he's proposed.

172
00:14:37,429 --> 00:14:54,949
[SPEAKER_17]: And I do think that this deal is damaging to this country, damaging to the rights we have at work and consumer protection and environmental protection in this country, and very damaging to manufacturing industry jobs all over Britain, some of which have already gone because of uncertainty over Brexit.

173
00:14:54,929 --> 00:14:56,832
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed, Mr Corbyn, Mr Johnson.

174
00:14:56,852 --> 00:15:02,860
[SPEAKER_04]: We have a deal that keeps the whole of the UK together as we come out of the EU.

175
00:15:02,940 --> 00:15:15,638
[SPEAKER_04]: And of course, Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party, be in no doubt about it, in order to secure power and the keys to number 10, are going to do a deal, and they probably already have done a deal, with Nicola Sturgeon and the SNP.

176
00:15:15,618 --> 00:15:18,000
[SPEAKER_04]: to form a Corbyn-Sturgeon coalition.

177
00:15:18,180 --> 00:15:28,069
[SPEAKER_04]: And the price of that deal, the price of Nicola Sturgeon's support, let's be in no doubt, she's made it absolutely clear, would be a second referendum on the union with Scotland.

178
00:15:28,309 --> 00:15:30,551
[SPEAKER_04]: I don't think we need another referendum on the union with Scotland.

179
00:15:30,831 --> 00:15:31,332
[SPEAKER_04]: I've ruled it out.

180
00:15:31,532 --> 00:15:32,653
[SPEAKER_04]: We had one in 2014.

181
00:15:32,693 --> 00:15:39,739
[SPEAKER_04]: The people of Scotland voted very substantially to stay in the most successful political partnership of the last 300 years.

182
00:15:39,919 --> 00:15:43,262
[SPEAKER_04]: Why put this country, this great country, through another referendum on Scotland?

183
00:15:43,422 --> 00:15:45,304
[SPEAKER_04]: And why have a second referendum?

184
00:15:45,284 --> 00:15:47,789
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, thank you very much indeed.

185
00:15:47,930 --> 00:15:48,371
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

186
00:15:48,391 --> 00:15:51,698
[SPEAKER_02]: That's time up on your first response to that.

187
00:15:51,738 --> 00:15:52,760
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed.

188
00:15:52,780 --> 00:15:57,510
[SPEAKER_02]: So just as a quick, you know, set something down in front of us, gentlemen.

189
00:15:57,551 --> 00:16:00,878
[SPEAKER_02]: For clarity, is the union more important than Brexit?

190
00:16:00,938 --> 00:16:01,960
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes or no?

191
00:16:03,037 --> 00:16:06,847
[SPEAKER_17]: I think I ought to be able to reply to this nonsense.

192
00:16:06,867 --> 00:16:07,729
[SPEAKER_02]: Will you be able to reply?

193
00:16:07,790 --> 00:16:09,213
[SPEAKER_17]: I'd just like to have it.

194
00:16:09,334 --> 00:16:12,643
[SPEAKER_17]: There's not going to be a coalition between Labour and the SNP.

195
00:16:12,803 --> 00:16:15,390
[SPEAKER_17]: There's not going to be a coalition between Labour and anybody else.

196
00:16:15,570 --> 00:16:19,240
[SPEAKER_17]: There are no deals that have been done and there will be no deals that are done.

197
00:16:21,515 --> 00:16:25,924
[SPEAKER_02]: For charity, is the union more important than Brexit, Mr Corbyn?

198
00:16:26,024 --> 00:16:38,330
[SPEAKER_17]: Our country is obviously very, very important and we have to bring this business to a close and that's why we're proposing a trade deal with Europe or staying in, one or the other, as a way of bringing this issue to a close.

199
00:16:38,350 --> 00:16:39,051
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr Johnson.

200
00:16:39,031 --> 00:16:46,519
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr. Bliski, the union is, of course, the most important thing, just to answer the question straight.

201
00:16:46,539 --> 00:16:47,740
[SPEAKER_04]: The union, and it's a fantastic thing.

202
00:16:48,521 --> 00:16:51,564
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm proud to be not only prime minister, but also minister for the union.

203
00:16:51,584 --> 00:17:02,155
[SPEAKER_04]: OK. Now, let's be clear that Jeremy Corbyn has said that he's open to a second referendum on Scotland early in the lifetime of the next parliament if he's head of the government.

204
00:17:02,455 --> 00:17:06,439
[SPEAKER_04]: And Nicola Sturgeon has made it absolutely clear that the price of her support

205
00:17:06,419 --> 00:17:09,463
[SPEAKER_04]: will be a referendum on Scotland in 2020.

206
00:17:10,044 --> 00:17:16,233
[SPEAKER_04]: So you're going to have a year of two referendums, one on Scotland and one... OK, let's allow Mr Corbyn to respond.

207
00:17:16,253 --> 00:17:17,795
[SPEAKER_02]: One on Scotland and one on the EU.

208
00:17:17,815 --> 00:17:19,117
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr Corbyn, if you do have to...

209
00:17:19,137 --> 00:17:19,978
[SPEAKER_02]: The opposite's the case, actually.

210
00:17:20,038 --> 00:17:28,951
[SPEAKER_02]: If you do have to get to a point where you have to make a deal with the SNP, Nicola Sturgeon has already said, don't pick up the phone unless you can guarantee a second independence referendum.

211
00:17:29,311 --> 00:17:32,055
[SPEAKER_02]: Can you rule it out before the end of the first year?

212
00:17:32,035 --> 00:17:45,319
[SPEAKER_17]: I've said there would be no deal with the SNP, there would be no support for a Scottish referendum in the early years of the next Labour government because I want to invest in Scotland and give Scotland the £70 billion it needs in capital investment.

213
00:17:45,439 --> 00:17:53,453
[SPEAKER_17]: If the SNP leadership choose to put the Conservative government back in office with its austerity programme, that's their choice.

214
00:17:54,023 --> 00:18:00,070
[SPEAKER_04]: I listened very carefully, as I always do, to Mr Corbyn.

215
00:18:00,110 --> 00:18:03,254
[SPEAKER_04]: I didn't hear him say he was going to rule out a referendum on Scotland.

216
00:18:03,274 --> 00:18:03,755
[SPEAKER_04]: Did you?

217
00:18:03,775 --> 00:18:06,358
[SPEAKER_04]: We're ruling out a referendum.

218
00:18:06,698 --> 00:18:14,888
[SPEAKER_04]: It's perfectly clear that the price of Nicola Sturgeon's support for the chaotic coalition that he would comprise is a second referendum.

219
00:18:14,908 --> 00:18:15,229
[SPEAKER_02]: OK, thank you.

220
00:18:15,249 --> 00:18:16,210
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's allow him to respond.

221
00:18:16,230 --> 00:18:16,871
[SPEAKER_04]: Can you rule it out?

222
00:18:16,891 --> 00:18:19,474
[SPEAKER_17]: We've witnessed nine years of chaotic coalitions already.

223
00:18:23,453 --> 00:18:28,000
[SPEAKER_02]: OK. Can I turn, please, to the issue of Northern Ireland?

224
00:18:28,080 --> 00:18:38,235
[SPEAKER_02]: In your hustings for your leadership race, Mr Johnson, you said, under no circumstances, whatever happens, will I allow the EU or anyone else to create any division down the Irish Sea?

225
00:18:38,455 --> 00:18:42,782
[SPEAKER_02]: You spoke at another conference a year ago, saying that that would damage the fabric of the union.

226
00:18:43,082 --> 00:18:43,723
[SPEAKER_02]: And now?

227
00:18:43,703 --> 00:18:46,288
[SPEAKER_02]: Here we have your deal that you've presented to Parliament.

228
00:18:46,388 --> 00:18:46,909
[SPEAKER_04]: Absolutely.

229
00:18:47,029 --> 00:18:56,807
[SPEAKER_04]: And that deal means that the whole of the UK can come out and do free trade deals around the world and do a great deal with our EU friends and partners, Northern Ireland included.

230
00:18:56,987 --> 00:18:58,911
[SPEAKER_04]: What the people of Northern Ireland don't know.

231
00:18:58,891 --> 00:19:00,755
[SPEAKER_02]: A trade deal down the Irish Sea?

232
00:19:00,855 --> 00:19:02,558
[SPEAKER_02]: A trade border down the Irish Sea?

233
00:19:02,578 --> 00:19:03,219
[SPEAKER_04]: Not at all.

234
00:19:03,259 --> 00:19:06,646
[SPEAKER_04]: Northern Ireland is part of the customs territory of the UK.

235
00:19:06,726 --> 00:19:08,409
[SPEAKER_04]: It's there in black and white.

236
00:19:08,429 --> 00:19:21,895
[SPEAKER_04]: And what the people of Northern Ireland do not know, and part of our tariff schedules and everything else, what the people of Northern Ireland do not know, and nor do the people of Ireland, is what kind of deal Jeremy Corbyn proposes to do.

237
00:19:21,875 --> 00:19:29,529
[SPEAKER_04]: And he's got 100 of his MPs, and we still don't know, by the way, what he proposes to do, nor whether he's in favour of it or against it.

238
00:19:29,950 --> 00:19:36,542
[SPEAKER_04]: We have 100 of his MPs who have already said that they would vote against it.

239
00:19:36,883 --> 00:19:39,147
[SPEAKER_04]: Most of the shadow cabinet are against the deal.

240
00:19:39,167 --> 00:19:39,868
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

241
00:19:39,888 --> 00:19:40,449
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr. Corbyn.

242
00:19:40,509 --> 00:19:41,651
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

243
00:19:41,712 --> 00:19:42,533
[SPEAKER_20]: A quick response.

244
00:19:42,513 --> 00:19:48,205
[SPEAKER_17]: The problem with what Mr Johnson just said is that he said exactly the opposite when he spoke to a DUP conference.

245
00:19:48,225 --> 00:19:51,191
[SPEAKER_17]: You said there would be no border down the Irish Sea.

246
00:19:51,271 --> 00:19:51,792
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, there is!

247
00:19:52,273 --> 00:19:52,934
[SPEAKER_04]: On the contrary.

248
00:19:53,375 --> 00:19:54,377
[SPEAKER_04]: On the contrary.

249
00:19:54,397 --> 00:19:58,345
[SPEAKER_04]: The whole of the UK comes out entire and perfect as I have.

250
00:19:58,325 --> 00:20:13,735
[SPEAKER_04]: said, we do free trade deals together, we take back control together, we have our own immigration system for instance, we can take back control of our borders and one of the many mysteries about Mr Corbyn's deal is would he take back control

251
00:20:13,715 --> 00:20:15,798
[SPEAKER_04]: of immigration, which people voted for.

252
00:20:15,818 --> 00:20:17,281
[SPEAKER_02]: We are going to stay on the issue of Brexit.

253
00:20:17,301 --> 00:20:19,404
[SPEAKER_04]: We are going to have an Australian-style points-based system.

254
00:20:19,424 --> 00:20:20,165
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

255
00:20:20,185 --> 00:20:21,507
[SPEAKER_02]: We're going to stay on the issue of Brexit.

256
00:20:21,547 --> 00:20:22,328
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

257
00:20:22,348 --> 00:20:24,452
[SPEAKER_02]: We're going to stay on this issue of Brexit.

258
00:20:24,532 --> 00:20:29,580
[SPEAKER_02]: And underlying this whole issue, of course, is the question of trust and leadership.

259
00:20:29,620 --> 00:20:31,923
[SPEAKER_02]: We have had hundreds of questions on this.

260
00:20:32,043 --> 00:20:34,587
[SPEAKER_02]: And with that in mind, it's over to Fahad Sayyed.

261
00:20:35,949 --> 00:20:41,578
[SPEAKER_16]: This whole nation will have watched you both throughout this campaign in utter despair.

262
00:20:41,744 --> 00:20:45,931
[SPEAKER_16]: At the heart of all of this is one very simple question.

263
00:20:45,951 --> 00:20:46,892
[SPEAKER_16]: How can we trust you?

264
00:20:54,324 --> 00:21:02,336
[SPEAKER_16]: Under your leadership the debate has become toxic and degraded with an appalling level of lies and childish abuse.

265
00:21:03,037 --> 00:21:04,039
[SPEAKER_16]: How can this nation

266
00:21:05,521 --> 00:21:17,279
[SPEAKER_16]: How can this nation trust you to have the personal integrity and individual strength of character to look after our country's interest, rescue us from this mess, and bring us back together?

267
00:21:18,441 --> 00:21:23,428
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much indeed.

268
00:21:23,448 --> 00:21:25,251
[SPEAKER_04]: Is it fired?

269
00:21:25,737 --> 00:21:26,959
[SPEAKER_04]: I think fine.

270
00:21:26,979 --> 00:21:30,484
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, thank you very much for a very important question.

271
00:21:30,544 --> 00:21:37,835
[SPEAKER_04]: And look, on the issue of trust, I think that trust in politics and in Parliament has been corroded.

272
00:21:38,215 --> 00:21:52,116
[SPEAKER_04]: And that is the most fundamental reason for that is because Parliament asked the people to vote on membership of the EU, and then Parliament has repeatedly refused to honour that promise, to respect the views of the people.

273
00:21:52,096 --> 00:21:58,303
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm afraid this, Jeremy Corbyn, Jeremy Corbyn and the Labour Party are now blocking Brexit.

274
00:21:58,343 --> 00:22:05,731
[SPEAKER_04]: The way I think, which is absolutely true, the way to restore trust in politics is to get Brexit done and move forward.

275
00:22:05,831 --> 00:22:08,254
[SPEAKER_04]: We have a great deal that enables us to do it.

276
00:22:08,794 --> 00:22:16,142
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm unclear as to why it's necessary to spend another year in a debate about Brexit, which is, as Farhan says, corrosive advice.

277
00:22:16,162 --> 00:22:16,723
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much.

278
00:22:16,763 --> 00:22:18,745
[SPEAKER_02]: Time is up, Mr Corbyn, your first response.

279
00:22:19,687 --> 00:22:22,934
[SPEAKER_17]: Trust is something that has to be earned.

280
00:22:23,696 --> 00:22:29,650
[SPEAKER_17]: And as a public representative, you have to listen to the people that elected you in the first place.

281
00:22:30,111 --> 00:22:33,479
[SPEAKER_17]: And you have to listen to people all over the country in all walks of life.

282
00:22:33,719 --> 00:22:37,628
[SPEAKER_17]: I spend a great deal of time traveling around the country listening to people.

283
00:22:37,996 --> 00:22:42,963
[SPEAKER_17]: be they chief executives, workers, people sweeping the street, or the homeless.

284
00:22:43,364 --> 00:22:45,908
[SPEAKER_17]: Everybody you meet knows something you don't know.

285
00:22:45,968 --> 00:22:57,385
[SPEAKER_17]: Leadership is about listening to people, trying to put their ideas into practice, and finally come to a decision in which you can take your country and our society forward.

286
00:22:57,405 --> 00:23:05,657
[SPEAKER_17]: My style of leadership is actually to listen to people and try and bring consensus together in my own party and, obviously, within Parliament because,

287
00:23:05,637 --> 00:23:09,121
[SPEAKER_17]: The issues we face of division in our society do have to be conquered.

288
00:23:09,321 --> 00:23:19,073
[SPEAKER_17]: They're not going to be conquered by diktat, but only by listening and taking us forward that way.

289
00:23:19,093 --> 00:23:19,494
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you very much.

290
00:23:19,514 --> 00:23:23,619
[SPEAKER_02]: Farhad put his finger right on something very specific in this question.

291
00:23:23,699 --> 00:23:29,446
[SPEAKER_02]: How can the nation trust you to have the personal integrity and the individual strength of character?

292
00:23:29,826 --> 00:23:31,408
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr Corbyn, how would you respond to that?

293
00:23:31,844 --> 00:23:41,852
[SPEAKER_17]: Well, I think we have to represent people, take decisions and be honest with people about why you're taking a decision that you are and how to bring people together.

294
00:23:42,113 --> 00:23:55,084
[SPEAKER_17]: My whole strategy on Brexit has been to recognise whether you voted remain and live in a private rented accommodation and in poor and in London, voted leave and you live in the North and are in the same situation, your issues are the same.

295
00:23:55,364 --> 00:23:59,287
[SPEAKER_17]: The problems of poverty, inequality and division within our society.

296
00:23:59,307 --> 00:24:01,429
[SPEAKER_17]: Bring people together, don't divide them.

297
00:24:03,670 --> 00:24:11,601
[SPEAKER_04]: I would just say to Farhan, look at what I have said I'm going to do as a politician and look what I've delivered.

298
00:24:11,621 --> 00:24:22,797
[SPEAKER_04]: Whether it was as Mayor of London or now as Prime Minister, I said that we would put 20,000 more police officers on the streets of our city, of our country, and we are recruiting them now.

299
00:24:23,178 --> 00:24:26,643
[SPEAKER_04]: I said we'd upgrade 20 hospitals and have 40 new hospitals.

300
00:24:26,863 --> 00:24:28,986
[SPEAKER_04]: That programme is going ahead.

301
00:24:28,966 --> 00:24:32,270
[SPEAKER_04]: We are uplifting funding for education across the country.

302
00:24:32,450 --> 00:24:36,555
[SPEAKER_04]: We're lifting up the living wage by its biggest ever expansion.

303
00:24:36,675 --> 00:24:40,859
[SPEAKER_04]: And I said we would deliver Brexit, and we will deliver Brexit.

304
00:24:40,879 --> 00:24:41,240
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

305
00:24:41,260 --> 00:24:44,684
[SPEAKER_04]: But we can only do it if we clear this parliamentary blockage.

306
00:24:44,704 --> 00:24:52,633
[SPEAKER_02]: Forgive me, Mr. Johnson, but this is about personal integrity and individual character.

307
00:24:53,053 --> 00:24:56,357
[SPEAKER_02]: Does the truth matter in this election?

308
00:24:57,012 --> 00:24:57,813
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it does.

309
00:24:58,254 --> 00:25:00,578
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think it very important.

310
00:25:00,598 --> 00:25:04,625
[SPEAKER_04]: I think it very important to hear from, I've been very clear about the deal that I've done.

311
00:25:04,866 --> 00:25:05,286
[SPEAKER_04]: There it is.

312
00:25:05,367 --> 00:25:06,028
[SPEAKER_04]: It's in black and white.

313
00:25:06,048 --> 00:25:06,709
[SPEAKER_04]: You can read it.

314
00:25:06,729 --> 00:25:07,250
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't know.

315
00:25:07,711 --> 00:25:09,394
[SPEAKER_04]: We don't know what Mr. Corbyn is proposing.

316
00:25:09,434 --> 00:25:10,596
[SPEAKER_04]: It's not just about Brexit.

317
00:25:10,616 --> 00:25:11,638
[SPEAKER_04]: He won't come clean.

318
00:25:11,658 --> 00:25:15,665
[SPEAKER_04]: He won't come clean with the electorate about what he is proposing to do.

319
00:25:15,685 --> 00:25:18,249
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr. Corbyn, allow Mr. Corbyn to respond, please.

320
00:25:18,269 --> 00:25:19,932
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you, Mr. Johnson.

321
00:25:19,912 --> 00:25:23,838
[SPEAKER_17]: I think we've been very clear on our policies in relation to Europe.

322
00:25:24,338 --> 00:25:33,492
[SPEAKER_17]: I think we're also very clear on all the other policies that will be unveiled in our manifesto on Thursday and they will be accompanied by a fully costed Grey Book with it.

323
00:25:33,512 --> 00:25:48,233
[SPEAKER_17]: So every pledge we make will be fully funded because I believe the British people deserve that knowledge, deserve to know what we're going to do and deserve a government that is actually not going to preside over rising homelessness, increasing inequality and chaos in the NHS.

324
00:25:48,433 --> 00:25:49,615
[SPEAKER_17]: Instead they're going to invest

325
00:25:49,595 --> 00:25:51,134
[SPEAKER_17]: in the future of this country.

326
00:25:53,476 --> 00:25:58,803
[SPEAKER_02]: Gentlemen, will you take some personal responsibility for the way the debate has unfolded in politics in this country?

327
00:25:58,843 --> 00:26:06,593
[SPEAKER_02]: We know, of course, Mr Johnson, that people point to the fact that you promised 40 times on record we'd be out of the EU on October the 31st.

328
00:26:07,294 --> 00:26:15,103
[SPEAKER_02]: One of your former chief of staffs from your time as London mayor said that you'd betrayed every person you'd ever had any dealings with.

329
00:26:15,123 --> 00:26:21,091
[SPEAKER_02]: And we know, Mr Corbyn, there are big questions about anti-Semitism within Labour, for example.

330
00:26:22,373 --> 00:26:22,673
[SPEAKER_02]: We know that...

331
00:26:22,653 --> 00:26:33,389
[SPEAKER_02]: The board of deputies of British Jews have said, you and your allies have been responsible for turning a once great party into a cesspit of anti-Semitism, were their words.

332
00:26:33,469 --> 00:26:38,937
[SPEAKER_02]: Can you both take some responsibility for the way the debate has turned in this country?

333
00:26:38,977 --> 00:26:42,923
[SPEAKER_17]: Anti-Semitism is an absolute evil and scourge within our society.

334
00:26:44,033 --> 00:26:47,519
[SPEAKER_17]: Racism in any form is a scourge in our society.

335
00:26:48,120 --> 00:26:53,930
[SPEAKER_17]: I have taken action in my party where anyone has committed any anti-Semitic acts or made any anti-Semitic statements.

336
00:26:54,271 --> 00:26:58,939
[SPEAKER_17]: They are either suspended or expelled from the party, and we've investigated every single case.

337
00:26:59,199 --> 00:27:05,611
[SPEAKER_17]: We do take this very, very seriously indeed, because I do not want to live in a society where racism is rife.

338
00:27:05,911 --> 00:27:07,594
[SPEAKER_17]: I understand and recognize

339
00:27:07,574 --> 00:27:16,349
[SPEAKER_17]: the desperate history of the Jewish people in the 20th century, which came about from an unrestriction of anti-Semitism in the 1920s.

340
00:27:16,429 --> 00:27:22,759
[SPEAKER_17]: We've got to stand up against racism in any form in our society.

341
00:27:22,779 --> 00:27:28,148
[SPEAKER_02]: And on the question of telling the truth in politics, Mr Johnson, your response to that?

342
00:27:28,128 --> 00:27:30,071
[SPEAKER_02]: The points that I put you on, those issues.

343
00:27:30,191 --> 00:27:40,206
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I'm just listening with open mouth to what Jeremy Corbyn had to say about what he's done to stamp out anti-Semitism in the Labour Party.

344
00:27:40,226 --> 00:27:45,834
[SPEAKER_04]: Because I'm afraid it's a complete failure of leadership, what's happened in the Labour Party with anti-Semitism.

345
00:27:45,954 --> 00:27:52,043
[SPEAKER_04]: But the failure of leadership is even worse when you look at what is happening on their Brexit policy.

346
00:27:52,023 --> 00:28:03,282
[SPEAKER_04]: Mr Johnson, before we go any further on this, what the people of this country want to hear is clarity about whether he believes in the deal that he is proposing to do.

347
00:28:03,362 --> 00:28:08,310
[SPEAKER_02]: And that matters deeply to the people in Brussels who will be doing that deal.

348
00:28:08,290 --> 00:28:12,495
[SPEAKER_02]: This was a question from Fahad about personal integrity and character.

349
00:28:12,535 --> 00:28:15,739
[SPEAKER_02]: So let's just try to take stock before we go for the ad break.

350
00:28:15,759 --> 00:28:23,829
[SPEAKER_02]: There are many people and many politicians, indeed, that feel that the nastiness of political debate in this country has simply got out of control.

351
00:28:24,250 --> 00:28:32,360
[SPEAKER_02]: Will you two tonight look at one another, and no matter who becomes prime minister, make a gesture to improve things today?

352
00:28:32,620 --> 00:28:35,023
[SPEAKER_02]: Could you make a pledge and promise?

353
00:28:35,003 --> 00:28:39,630
[SPEAKER_17]: that whoever becomes Prime Minister improves the nature of debate in this country.

354
00:28:39,871 --> 00:28:49,206
[SPEAKER_17]: The debate in Parliament before Parliament was dissolved was vicious and horrible and some terrible remarks were made particularly to and about women MPs.

355
00:28:49,226 --> 00:28:58,581
[SPEAKER_17]: I asked the Speaker to convene a meeting of all party leaders, Mr Johnson sent a representative there and we agreed that this was unacceptable conduct and I absolutely agree with that.

356
00:28:58,561 --> 00:28:58,882
[SPEAKER_17]: Thank you.

357
00:28:58,902 --> 00:29:02,468
[SPEAKER_17]: Will you both make a pledge to improve things?

358
00:29:02,488 --> 00:29:09,181
[SPEAKER_02]: And perhaps gentlemen, could you shake hands to make a pledge to improve politics?

359
00:29:09,201 --> 00:29:11,546
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you very much indeed.

